    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1968-12-21T23:59:59-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1968-12-21T00:00:00-05:00" n="180"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d180">
                <head>180. Memorandum From Director of the Bureau of the Budget <persName
                        type="from">Zwick</persName> to President <persName corresp="#p_JLB1"
                        type="to">Johnson</persName>
                    <note n="1" type="source" xml:id="d180fn1">Source: Johnson Library, National
                        Security File, Country File, Bolivia, Vol. IV, Memoranda, January
                        1966–December 1968. Confidential.</note>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>Washington</placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian"
                            when="1968-12-21">December 21, 1968</date>.</dateline>
                </opener>
                <list type="subject">
                    <head>SUBJECT</head>
                    <item>Proposed P.L. 480 Program for Bolivia</item>
                </list>
                <p>
                    <persName corresp="#p_FOL1">Orville Freeman</persName> request your approval to
                    negotiate a $6.8 million P.L. 480 sales agreement with Bolivia for wheat/wheat
                    flour and tobacco.<note n="2" xml:id="d180fn2">Attached, but not printed.</note>
                    Repayment will be in dollars over twenty years with 5 percent down. There will
                    be no currency use payment under the Purcell amendment since no additional
                    currency is needed at this time.</p>
                <p>Last June, <gloss target="#t_AID1">AID</gloss> authorized a $4.5 million
                    Supporting Assistance loan to Bolivia as the initial budgetary support for an
                    18-month fiscal reform and stabilization program jointly developed among <gloss
                        target="#t_AID1">AID</gloss>, the <gloss target="#t_IMF1">IMF</gloss>, and
                    the Government of Bolivia. This P.L. 480 agreement will constitute <gloss
                        target="#t_AID1">AID</gloss>’s major 1969 resource input for Bolivia and as
                    such <hi rend="italic">forms an important continuing element in the fiscal
                        reform program.</hi>
                </p>
                <p>
                    <hi rend="italic">The local currency proceeds from this agreement will be
                        earmarked on a standby basis for budget support in <gloss target="#t_CY1"
                            >CY</gloss> 1969</hi> should the need arise. Thus, <hi rend="italic">the
                        P.L. 480 agreement should eliminate the need for additional Supporting
                        Assistance funds.</hi> If the need for budget support does not arise, the
                    proceeds will be used in the agricultural sector.</p>
                <p>State/<gloss target="#t_AID1">AID</gloss> has determined that Bolivia’s resources
                    are not being diverted to unnecessary military expenditures to a degree which
                    materially interferes with its development and that neither U.S. development
                    assistance nor P.L. 480 sales proceeds are being diverted by Bolivia to military
                    purposes.</p>
                <p>Because this P.L. 480 agreement will support and reinforce the fiscal reform
                    program and will substitute for dollar assistance, <hi rend="italic">I recommend
                        that you approve negotiation of the agreement.</hi>
                    <note n="3" xml:id="d180fn3">The approve option is checked. <persName
                            corresp="#p_RWW1">Rostow</persName> appended a handwritten note to a
                        December 24 memorandum to <persName corresp="#p_JLB1">Johnson</persName>
                        recommending approval of the package, indicating: “Final approval by
                        telephone, 27 December, 1968.” (Johnson Library, National Security File,
                        Country File, Bolivia, Vol. IV, Memoranda, January 1966–December
                        1968)</note>
                </p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>Charles J. Zwick</signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
